headline: Entrepreneur | AI/ML Software Engineer | Researcher | Innovator | (Connect only with a personalized note)
summary: Gunarakulan Gunaretnam is a highly passionate professional technologist in computer science and engineering. He is a software engineer, entrepreneur, researcher, innovator, educator, community worker for tech-related projects, he is well-known for developing artificial intelligence and machine learning software solutions for business problems and social challenges.  He was introduced to computers at the age of 8, and he started to learn programming at the age of 11. He built his first commercial software product at the age of 15 for a finance & leasing company.    As a software engineer, he has worked on more than 60+ small and large commercial and non-commercial software projects for business sectors and, for his own experiences. He worked on a large number of software applications that involve finance, healthcare, supermarket, transport, social media and etc.    As an entrepreneur, he co-founded 3 organizations in the sector of software development & engineering services, online education + mentoring, and a social mission on empowering underprivileged communities in technology.   As a researcher, he published 3 research papers in the field of artificial intelligence, machine learning, computer vision, Human interaction & Facial Expression Detection (Training Computers to Recognize Facial Expressions of Humans), and Analyzing Hate Speeches in Audio (Training Computers to Identify Hate Speeches in Audio and Text Formats on social media).  As an innovator, he co-created many prototypes and systems that are used to solve real-world problems in business sectors. He built an effective computer vision system for facemask and social distance monitoring purposes during the covid-19 situation.   As an educator, he has trained several young innovators and mentored a large number of students in the domain of computer science and technology.  As a community worker, he co-founded an organization called AI4Life that’s primary scope is to empower, train, and make technology revolution in the rural areas of Sri Lanka. He is affiliated with many non-profit organization that works for nature & the ocean, women empowerment in tech, social innovations, and technology empowerments.

headline: ML Engineer at BusinessOptics
location_name: City of Cape Town, Western Cape, South Africa
summary: I'm a tech optimist looking to be at the place where recent advancements (whether that be neural networks or word-embeddings) change an industry. One day, I'd like to create such a place myself.  I'm currently employed as Machine Learning Engineer at BusinessOptics. Here I've been responsible for building various functionality in the AI space, including entity-resolution of people, credit-modelling and 2-phase ANN searching.
address: City of Cape Town, Western Cape, South Africa
organization_description_1: Built a vast data pipeline for sanctioned and politically exposed entities plus matching and entity-resolution algorithms. Later transitioned to building backend and frontend integrations to these. Development in Python (Pandas, Tensorflow, Django, Dash) with a touch of frontend languages (JS, HTML, CSS, TurboLinks). Other main tech: AWS, Docker, Terraform, PostgreSQL.
organization_description_2: Researched and now developed a full data-based solution to accomplish straight-through claims processing.  This involved replacing 3 tasks traditionally performed by humans: ● Item identification: items descriptions would usually be researched and identified online. I've built up a database of almost 200k items by scraping sites such as GSMArena and Amazon, parsing them by means of various NLP techniques and spec classification neural networks which continues to learn from new unlabelled data (some have now reached more than 99.9% accuracy, which is remarkable in the field of text classification). ● Item succession: most claims are done on models that are no longer available for retail. I built a model to predict succession confidence scores and fine-tuned it with using training data and simple regression techniques. ● Item matcher: in order to automatically match an item in our database with a quote I scraped from a company such a Takealot, I needed to build another model which does advanced processing on the name, specs, release date, price, images and all other data we have to compare.  Development in Python (with Tensorflow, Scikit-learn, Scrapy and Django) plus PostgreSQL.
organization_description_3: Built 9 websites professionally, from simple 5-page static sites to e-commerce sites using web frameworks such as Magento, Shopify and Wordpress. Languages used: Javascript, PHP, HTML, CSS and MySQL.
organization_description_4: I worked as a full-stack developer on the ABALOBI project. ABALOBI enables artisanal fishers to sell their catch to upper-class restaurants without any middleman. One of my main responsibilities was designing and building the front-end experience of Hook2Cook, a web app that visually tells restaurant-goers the story behind the fish on their plate - and, more importantly, the story of the fisherman who caught it. During my time on the project, ABALOBI was featured in major South African newspapers as well as the primetime national television news show, Carte Blanche. Here it was explained as the "uber" and even "tinder for fish". Media, hey?  Developed using the Javascript-based MEAN stack (MongoDB, ExpressJS, Angular, NodeJS) plus Python for analytics.
organization_description_5: Produced 7 videos professionally using Adobe Premiere Pro and Sony Vegas.

Dojos are run by coordinators (Champions) at businesses, schools, libraries, universities, councils and community centres. Dojos provide fun, free and social open learning environments where young people can meet others with similar interests, develop 21st century skills and build creative projects of their own choice using digital technology.  A Dojo is NOT a class or workshop. There is no curriculum. Instead, Dojos offer open, free and unstructured club settings in which young people can follow their own interests, meet like-minded people and develop self-directed learning habits with the support of Champions and Mentors. headline: ML Engineer, Recommendations at Twitter
summary: Currently a Machine Learning Engineer at Twitter in London. I previously worked at IBM Research as an AI Resident.  I graduated from Georgia Tech with a MS in Computer Science, specialized in Machine Learning. I have also completed a Master Degree in Computer Engineering at INSA Lyon.  I am very interested in translating research ideas into actionable, user-focused products.
organization_description_3: The AI Residency program provides an opportunity to conduct research and engineering in recent topics in Artificial Intelligence. I am focused on 2 lines of work:  Compositional Generalization: We investigate in a new paper whether neural networks can generalize compositionally like people do, by being able to discriminate among different classes of visual objects.  I had several duties for this paper: * I helped design the experiments and the hypotheses they test, * I co-wrote the generation code to create the image samples we used in the experiments, * I wrote the code for training the models, tracking the statistics and saving the results to file, * Finally, I helped analyze the results and discuss them in the paper.  See publication: https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.09437   Transfer Learning in Visual Reasoning: Building on my previous work on Visual Question Answering, and extending to Video Reasoning, we propose a new taxonomy on 3 axes: temporal transfer, features transfer and reasoning transfer. I took an active role in setting up the experiments and collecting the results, reusing the MI-Prometheus library I have co-developed.  See publication:  https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.11938
organization_description_4: Co-developped an open-source framework, called Mi-Prometheus, aiming at enabling reproducible Machine Learning Research. This framework relies on PyTorch and extensively uses its mechanisms for the distribution of computations on CPUs/GPUs.  Accepted publication: NeurIPS 2018 "ML Open Source Software" workshop (https://openreview.net/pdf?id=rJgZ0tpN2X) Received a travel grant to present the poster.  Also worked on Visual Question Answering and how to better use compositional reasoning to solve this problem: - Reimplemented a state-of-the-art model (https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.03067), - Reduced training time by 10%  Accepted publication: NeurIPS 2018 "Visually Grounded Interaction & Language" workshop (https://arxiv.org/abs/1811.06529).
organization_description_5: First experience in a research environment: - Assessed the performance per watt of a computational simulations platform (FEniCS) on an ARM architecture. - Reduced the run-time of main computation by 24%, using load balancing to better use the different CPU cores.

headline: AI & ML Engineer at Delta Air Lines
summary: I am a post-graduate in Computer Science and Data Processing from IIT Kharagpur. I also have a master's degree in Applied Mathematics. I've been working as a Data Scientist for almost three years now.   In my present organization, I have researched and developed a multi-label, multi-class classifier using deep learning techniques to detect diagnosis (ICD) and procedure (CPT) codes in medical reports of real patients. These codes help in billing for medical insurance claims.  At Omega, I am also a part of the recruitment panel to select the right candidates for the Data Science team.  Previously, as a Data Scientist at Oxstren Wearable Technologies Pvt. Ltd. I devised algorithms that can detect and identify rhythmic exercises and count repetitions and measure parameters such as Energy Burnt, Peak Velocity, Peak Force etc. during a gym session in real-time. Most importantly, I wrote these algorithms in such a way that they can run on Android and iOS devices as well as on WatchOS and WearOS platforms.    To enhance my knowledge further, I completed Machine Learning courses offered by Stanford University and Washington University provided through Coursera. As assignments for these courses, I implemented a Movie Recommender System using Collaborative Filtering algorithm, built a Spam Classifier using Support Vector Machine, implemented Principal Component Analysis on 100 grayscale face images and reduced data size by ten times keeping the general structure of the images intact, implemented a Gaussian Model to detect anomalous servers in a network.     I love watching great movies from all over the world as they explore who we are and what we can be. I am a great Cricket and Football fan too. And, like everyone else, I love listening to good music.  I aspire to build Artificial Intelligence to help us all in our day to day lives and to explore beyond the limitations we thought were unattainable.
organization_2: Omega Healthcare Management Services Private Limited
organization_description_2: Data Science Research and Development  1. Detection of diagnosis (ICD) and procedure (CPT) codes in medical reports: Built a multi-label, multi-class classifier using a Convolutional Neural Network architecture with Attention. PyTorch was used as the Deep Learning Framework.   2. Extraction of n-grams from medical reports for interpretability of diagnosis detection: Used Word Embedding method to train word2vec on our custom medical data and built an algorithm to extract n-grams from medical reports to support detected diagnosis code.  3. Automated correction of diagnosis information from medical reports: Wrote an algorithm that can automatically discard irrelevant information in diagnosis description in medical records and construct a precise description of diagnosis.  4. Automated sequencing of diagnosis codes based on standard guidelines: Using standard guidelines for sequencing of diagnosis codes in a medical report, built a rule-based algorithm which can sequence the diagnosis codes by itself.  5. Automated diagnosis summary preparation of medical reports: Designed and implemented a neural network architecture with TensorFlow to summarize a medical report into precise diagnosis information only.
organization_description_3: Algorithm Research and Development:  1. Real-time Detection of The Start and End points of Rhythmic Exercises Using Accelerometer on WatchOS and WearOS: The algorithm discards unrhythmic movements during an exercise session and automatically detects the start and endpoints of an exercise set in real-time.  2. Identification of Rhythmic Patterns in Realtime on Android and iOS: Built an algorithm that can gradually learn the varying patterns of an exercise using precise features extracted from accelerometer and gyroscope signals and identify it accurately in realtime.  3. Repetition Count with Peaks and Valleys in Rhythmic Activity in Real-time on WatchOS and WearOS: The peak and the valley of every repetition are detected and essential parameters such as peak velocity, peak force, energy burnt, etc. are calculated.   4. Development of a Single Class Classifier using “Mahalanobis Distance”: It is used to differentiate rhythmic-non exercise motion from exercise motion.  5. Development of a Supervised Clustering Algorithm: It categorizes different rhythmic activities based on their similarities in the movement pattern.  Application Development:  1. Did Native Development in C++ to build intelligence using Machine Learning on Android, iOS, WatchOS, and WearOS.  2. Built a Web API on a Linux Server residing in Cloud. The API is used to run algorithms that can automatically log exercise details at the end of a gym session.
organization_description_4: Analysed Google Analytics data to understand how widgets work regarding traffic engagement on a website and how and where to place them. headline: Staff ML Engineer at Sensibill
summary: I received my computer science PhD from Nanyang Technological University in Singapore. During my PhD I was researching on machine learning based approaches applicable on large scale temporal and spatiotemporal problems. Soon after my graduation I joined Grab, one of the leading tech companies in South East Asia. As a lead data scientist in Transport tech family at Grab, I was researching, developing and deploying large scale data science and ML solutions across 8 countries and millions of customers. I’m currently working as applied data scientist and ML engineer in Sensibill, developing and deploying ML solutions in Fintech domain. When I'm not working I play volleyball, practice tennis and try to learn new languages.
organization_description_1: Sensibill is a receipt management company that provides a receipt extraction and digitization solution to financial institutions. With this service, end users are able to capture their purchase receipts and invoices, keep track of their expenses and organize their spendings efficiently.  At Data and AI team in Sensibill, we leverage anonymized data in the receipts and use machine learning solutions to extract user and merchant level insights, enrich the extracted data using various NLP techniques and provide personalized insights to the users and clients.
organization_description_2: In Grab we use data and technology to improve everything from transportation to payments and logistics across a region of more than 620 million people. Working with governments, drivers, passengers, and charities, we aim to unlock the true potential of the region by solving problems that hinder progress. Grab began as a taxi-hailing app in 2012, but has extended its product platform to include private car services (GrabCar & GrabShare), motorcycle taxis (GrabBike), social carpooling (GrabHitch) and last mile delivery (GrabExpress). We are focused on pioneering new commuting alternatives for drivers and passengers with an emphasis on speed, safety, and reliability. Grab currently offers services in Singapore, Indonesia, Philippines, Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam; however, it also has R&D offices in Bangalore, Beijing, & Seattle.
organization_description_3: Thesis title: Machine Learning-Based approaches for Large-Scale Temporal Data Analytics. --- As a PhD scholar in the field of Data Science and Machine Learning, I have been part of Data Management and Analytics Graduate Lab (DMAL) in Nanyang Technological University (NTU) and Data Analytics Department (DAD) in Institute for Infocomm Research, A*Star. During my PhD, I have worked on multiple projects related to data stream mining and Machine Learning based approaches for temporal data analytics. My projects involved optimization, mathematical formulations, distributed and parallel machine learning for large scale data and deep learning based approaches for spatio-temporal forecasting and abnormal event detection problems.

education_description_1: •	Master’s Thesis: Real Time Anomaly Detection of Crowds in CCTV Stream| Deep Learning-TensorFlow/ CNN/ Autoencoders/ GANs   •	Real time detection of anomalous behavior in crowded scenarios. Development of a self-supervised system that minimizes the user intervention.   A system was developed that is capable of detecting anomalous behaviors in crowded areas. When a CCTV stream is fed to the system, if an anomalous behavior is detected, it automatically flags the frames that contain the anomalous incident. This system needs minimum supervision such that this can be installed to monitor a given scene and the system automatically adapts itself to determine anomalies in them. This is a context independent system, which means that this is not trained specifically to cater a certain type of scenario, but to adapt according to the present norm and filter out abnormalities in real time. The project scored an ’A’ on the final evaluation

The system developed was an intelligent traffic controlling and recommendation system which observes oncoming vehicles and waiting pedestrians to decide and propose suitable traffic light switching. This was developed to parallelly observe two CCTV streams and make decisions in real time. A number image processing techniques were used to reduce the region of interest and machine learning models were trained to detect human and vehicle presence in them. Based on the detection results, current vehicle flow was evaluated against the pedestrians waiting in crowds and those metrics were used to intelligently decide on traffic controlling recommendations. The project scored an ’A+’ on the final evaluation.

I enjoy implementing research ideas, sometimes incorporating them in practical applications, and communicating my implementation details through articles.  I advocate for highly readable and self-contained code. I primarily use Python for programming. I am proficient in TensorFlow and a beginner in PyTorch. Two accolades I take pride in:  - Intel Software Innovator - Google Developers Expert (GDE) in Machine Learning  I have a flair for open-source initiatives. In particular, I have made contributions to TensorFlow Hub (https://tfhub.dev/s?publisher=sayakpaul), Keras Examples (https://git.io/JGQTx), TensorFlow Addons (https://git.io/JuUOr), and Neural Structured Learning (https://git.io/JuUOd). Planning and people. I am an easy-going, amiable, and organized person. I have always enjoyed working with others. I backward schedule all my tasks with adequate buffer and be organized to ensure good synergy in the team.  2.	I strongly believe every day is an opportunity to learn something new. While working at Robert Bosch with my background in embedded systems, I got a chance to explore how we can use AI and ML to improve our everyday work. This fascinated me and I decided to pursue the field further by studying machine learning and data science at grad school. One year through, I have acquired the following skills through the courses, projects, and research groups: •	Supervised learning algorithms like linear regression, support vector machine, random forest •	Frameworks like TensorFlow, Keras, and PyTorch •	Programming languages – Python and C++ •	Deep Learning – Artificial NN, Recurrent NN, Convolutional NN, Generative Adversarial Networks •	Python libraries – Numpy, Pandas, sklearn, Librosa, Matplotlib, Seaborn •	Knowledge of statistics, probability, and linear algebra •	Database management systems – MySQL •	Data structures and algorithms  3.	Touching the finish line. Having put in detailed planning and work into my tasks, I do not let hurdles stop me from completing the task. Regardless of the result, I will leave no stone unturned in the process. headline: ML Engineer - Distributed Systems
summary: Versatile data scientist and engineer, I enjoy research as much as software development. Areas of expertise include applications of machine learning algorithms including and especially building, optimising and deploying them in production systems. I'm also experienced in building distributed data pipelines involving high volume ETL workloads.  Recent work include ( AdTech ) building algorithms combining game theoretic approaches with standard reinforcement learning techniques for Optimal Decision making and Causal Inference in Imperfect Information Systems (online Ad Campaign engines) with partially observable states.  I was also involved in building Distributed data pipelines capable of handling high volume Spatio-Temporal ETL workloads (smartphone geo-timestamped feeds) for deriving consumer behavioural patterns and creating audience segments which can be used of strategic decision making and micro-targeting.    Programming Languages: Python | JAVA | C++   Databases: MySQL | Cassandra | PostgreSQL  ML Frameworks:  scikit-learn | numpy | Pandas | TensorFlow | PyTorch   Distributed Systems: Spark | Hadoop | Kafka | Redis | RabbitMQ | Celery | ElasticSearch | Docker | Kubernetes | Airflow  API: FastAPI | gRPC Logging and Monitoring: ELK | Splunk | Sentry | New Relic Cloud Stack: Azure | AWS Version Control: Git
organization_description_1: I created, led, and was a primary developer for the "Location Intel Roadmap", a year long R&D into leveraging geo-timestamped GPS data feeds from smartphone apps for deriving consumer behavioural patterns and creating audience segments, which can be used for strategic decision making and micro-targeting.  - Built distributed data pipelines capable of handling high volume Spatio-Temporal ETL workloads (billion+ records/day), in a multi-modal geo-timestamped setting. - Worked on Spark Optimizations leading to 30x throughput improvements of Search and Localization( POI ) and Mobility computations. While also dropping compute costs for those pipelines 4x. - Built POI pipelines leveraging Spark, Geospatial Indexing with Matrix Factorization techniques for identifying hyperlocal trends based on user's geographic movement patterns and temporal consumption behaviours. - Implemented comprehensive production Observability (logging, metrics & alerts)   Built algorithms around multitouch attribution in Ad-Tech and using them for Adaptive Experimentation, Causal Inferencing and Optimizing Ad-Campaigns.  - Implemented Contextual Bandits in an adaptive experimentation setting for identifying high-dimensional performing segments of Ad-Campaigns. - The solution addresses how to estimate the incremental effect of an Ad-Campaigns, and can attribute incremental effects to individual impressions based on high-dimensional characteristics of the ad in the customer journey (campaign Funnel), and carry over effects. - This attribution allows to optimize Marketing Campaigns by identifying optimal budget re-routing strategies for maximizing incremental effects. - Implemented Off-Policy Counterfactual Estimators and Rank-Aware Metrics for Inference

I'm doing whatever I can to shape a world where our transport is all-electric and fully self-driven to help people live safer and longer lives. Lives with increased freedom, more free time, and heightened peace of mind.   In general, I love attacking tough and unsolved problems, irrespective of the industry, with an emphasis on improving people's lives.   I enjoy diving headfirst into new technologies and domains. This has allowed me to learn a ton of languages, engineering concepts, and paradigms, ranging from Artificial Intelligence to Microservices to Big Data to Machine Learning to RESTful APIs to Autonomous Vehicles to Software Defined Networks.   I'm proficient in Python, C++, Node.js, JavaScript, Databases, Large-Scale Distributed Systems, ML Platform Infrastructures, Big Data, Flask, Django, Celery, REST APIs, PostgreSQL, Docker, A/B testing, Micro-Services, AWS, GCP, Redis, Kafka, Cassandra and more.
organization_description_1: Self driving cars!  Currently working on building a world-class Machine Learning Platform for mining raw data coming from our vehicles.   We're on a mission to build the world’s most advanced self-driving vehicles to safely connect people with the places, things and experiences they care about.   I'm motivated by the potential to save millions of lives, rethink our cities and give people back their time.  The languages and frameworks I use and have used in the past are: Python, Node.js, Typescript, C++, Docker, Kubernetes, gRPC, PostgreSQL, GCP
organization_description_2: As a Software Engineer at Cisco I helped build and launch features that helped customers easily setup and scale their data centers.   This was called ACI (Application Centric Infrastructure) and it was an SDN (Software Defined Networking) framework that helped in abstracting away many details of machines, deployment, networking and operating systems from the application developer. This entire process was shifted from being machine-oriented to being application-oriented where we took care of the nitty gritty for you.   This dramatically improves application deployment and introspection. The key advantages include multi tenancy, simplifying operations at scale, while providing full visibility and end-to-end troubleshooting.  The languages, frameworks, and technologies I used included: C++, Python, JavaScript, Typescript, Virtualization, Docker and RESTful API services.
organization_description_3: Some of the projects I worked on include -  Study of Cross-Traffic Perturbations  • Programmed and generated numerous packet clustering scenarios on MATLAB by employing geometric, exponential and log-normal distributions of cross-traffic • Designed a new router model and investigated the effect of cross-traffic perturbation on target traffic • Implemented and tested the protocol against the router model and established that deterministic form of user traffic was most resilient to cross-traffic perturbations  Asynchronous Multicasting  • Coded and implemented a novel system in C++ to provide on-demand viewing of a video while multicasting to service multiple users with overlapping needs • Implemented algorithms that increased multicast rate from 3 Mbps to 54 Mbps  Worked under Prof. Aaron Wagner and Prof. Kevin Tang

headline: Senior ML Software Engineer at Twitter
summary: Huasen Wu is currently a software engineer at Twitter, working on recommendation.  He received his B.S. and Ph.D. degrees from the School of Electronic and Information Engineering, Beihang University, Beijing, in 2007 and 2014, respectively. From 2014 to 2017, he was a Postdoctoral Researcher working with Prof. Xin Liu at the Department of Computer Science, University of California, Davis. From December 2010 to January 2012, he was a visiting student at UC Davis, and from October 2012 to January 2014, he worked as a research intern at Wireless and Networking Group, Microsoft Research Asia.
organization_description_3: Doing research on jointly machine learning and decision making for online optimization for recommendation, advertising, and networking.  Projects:  Online Recommendation with Budget Constraints and Side-information (05/2014 – Present) • Designed Bayesian sampling algorithms for recommendation systems with pairwise feedback • Designed O(N log N) algorithms that achieve order-optimal performance in constrained contextual bandits • Published papers at NIPS'15, NIPS'16  From Prediction to Action: Data-Driven Network Optimization (05/2014 – Present) • Constructed user behavior and QoE models based on network data • Designed resource allocation algorithms to improve the user QoE (↓~50% complaining users) • Published papers at KDD'16, WiOpt'16
organization_description_4: Visited Coordinated Science Lab (CSL), and did research in data-driven optimization and machine learning. During this visit, I tried to study the design and analysis techniques in machine learning problems, such as multi-arm bandits and best-expert advice problems, and found potential research problems.
organization_description_5: Designed and analyzed scheduling policies in SQL DataSync and cellular networks.   For DataSync, I analyzed the trace collected in the trial stage for identifying the design issues and performance bottleneck, and designed delay-minimizing scheduling policy without knowledge of processing time and with preemption cost.   For cellular networks, I focused on the design of scheduling policies for wireless networks with flow-level dynamics and deadlines. I investigated the asymptotic behavior in the many-source regime and studied decomposition techniques and design distributed scheduling policies. This is also the topic of my PhD dissertation.
education_description_1: Research interests: RFID, cognitive radio communications, data link, Machine-to-Machine communications, and opportunistic scheduling in wireless networks. Title of dissertation: Flow-Level Opportunistic Scheduling with QoE Guarantee in Wireless Networks Co-supervised by Prof. Youguang Zhang and Prof. Xin Liu (UC Davis).

headline: Senior ML Engineer
summary: I have a passion for AI and transforming its research into impactful real-world applications. I am experienced in building scalable, fault-tolerant distributed systems that deal with large data volumes, having been programming for 20 years, including 10 with Python, 6 with the PyData stack, and 3 with Spark.  With data science, I have full-stack experience spanning the construction of robust ETL and data pipelines, and the development of associated visualization tools based on real-world data. In summary, I build data products, productionise data science solutions, and have extensive experience in the field of data engineering and machine learning.  Key Specialities: Machine Learning | Data Science | AWS | Python | SQL | Java | Jupyter | Spark | Data Engineering | Data Analysis | Research
organization_description_1: Operationalised deep learning ML projects. The ‘Doc2Data’ product curated unstructured data from pdf documents and outputted meaningful interactive charts for the clients. This used Facebook’s Detectron2 (PyTorch) for the deep learning backbone, as well as OpenCV for simpler image processing.  Built and configured a multi-tenant machine learning environment on AWS using Kubeflow, Kubernetes and Docker (with JupyterLabs for data scientists).  Set up and developed ML pipelines using Kubeflow Pipelines.  Developed APIs and models for multivariate time-series forecasts. These were used in interactive forecasting dashboards for insurance analysts to manage the risk of their portfolios. I also built automated ML pipelines to highlight the top models per portfolio.  CI (TeamCity) for ML projects and pipelines.
organization_description_2: Initiated the startup's data science function. I grew out the team and designed and implemented the architecture behind the ML systems. This streamlined development work and led to ongoing LTV, Retention, ARPU and IMPU improvements.  Productionised ML models in both the cloud and edge (mobile) devices, embedded within our SDK. Models include predicting LTVs, categorising new games based on their screenshots and an optimised monetisation setup for games.  Integrated segmentation within AB Testing, so that each user segment can be served the optimal player experience.  Evangelised good research practices, enabled data-driven decisions and fostered a fun and collaborative culture.
organization_description_3: Grew the company’s Data Science department, and managed the Operational Data Science team.  Trained, coached and mentored individuals within my team and around the company as well as enforced best practices of data science and data engineering.  Serviced the teams: Pricing, Market Making, Trading Platform, HR as well as senior execs.  Built data products and data science solutions, including:  Marketing Tracking & Analytics , ROMI, Single Client Model , Client ID Resolution , Collaborative Filtering (Recommender System) , Pricing Latency , Chatbot , Propensity Models   Provided first visibility of many metrics within the company, in an automated and reliable system .

summary: Hello! I'm Bruno, and I have a passion for computational modelling. I currently develop and test Neural Network models in order to predict the immune response in mammals.  I am presently seeking job opportunities for 2021, so please do not hesitate to contact me if you see me fit for the role!  Examples of my work/research can be found in:  GitHub: http://bit.ly/2ReKC4H Google Scholar: http://bit.ly/2NOkyLL ResearchGate: http://bit.ly/3axNiSI
address: Buenos Aires, Buenos Aires Province, Argentina
organization_description_1: Development of neural network models for the prediction of immune responses in mammals. Such models enable the prediction of antigen-host interactions for a specific immune profile (determined by its Major Histocompatibility Complex -MHC- variants).  My daily tasks include:  ● Develop preprocessing pipelines to extract train and test data from biological sequecing experiments (usually in the order of 10+ million entries). ● Improve existing algorithms by means of incorporating additional data, new features and/or architecture modifications. ● Standardize training and testing pipelines for such algorithms. ● Perform quantitative analyses for the train and independent test results. ● Validate such results via publications on scientific journals of measurable impact. ● Finish the development cycle with the deployment of a commercial product and/or of a public web-server.  All these tasks are performed using a combination of inherited C code and custom-developed Python pipelines (using the NumPy+Pandas+Scikit+Tensorflow stack). On the other hand, since all my work is executed and stored in Computerome (Danish supercomputing center), I am familiarised with batch system operations and parallelization strategies.

headline: Software Engineer - Python, AI and ML at emids
summary: I have always had flair for two things: math and music. Exploring data to deduce relationships between variables, using plots to visualise those relationships, and driving insights through these processes give me immense joy. Singing my heart out and composing melodies accompanied by my guitar are blissful.  Mathematics is my first love, and music, my second. But what is the connection between these two significantly diverse fields? Both music and math, are forms of art! Only when one views both these fields as forms of art, could one relish their beauty!  Currently, I am developing an appetite to appreciate Data Science and Analytics as forms of art. It is all about how creative a Data Scientist can be. The tools/softwares available in the market are equivalent to colours and paintbrushes available to a painter, instruments available to a musician and ingredients available to a cook. The output is solely dependent on their methodology. Different artists exploit their tools in different ways. There is no " one right way ".

headline: RTL Design Engineer at Lemurian Labs | Consultant at UoM
summary: I love tackling difficult problems, designing and implementing solutions, while self-learning and building intuition in necessary topics. I am passionate about teaching the topics I learnt and conveying my intuitive understanding of difficult topics to the students. I also enjoy community service, backpacking and hiking.  As an undergraduate, I built a systolic CNN accelerator with RTL to perform 153 billion multiply-adds a second on a ZYNQ FPGA. I designed a mass manufacturable edge-solution for the problem of vision-based adaptive traffic control and built award-winning algorithms which we have patented. The webinar series through which I taught what I learnt in SystemVerilog, received an overwhelmingly positive response. Currently, I am working at an international startup that is set to compete with NVIDIA and Google, with experts in signal processing, ML and software engineering, to build a chip to accelerate AI inference. education_description_1: My PhD research aimed at an analytic framework for dialectical interactions between software agents (AI agents) in uncertain environments, focusing, among others, on modelling and strategic aspects in such interactions.  To strategise in this context an agent needs to be aware (at least to some valid extent) of the possible knowledge of its opponents, so as to simulate the possible ways based on which a dialogue may evolve and accordingly follow the path that leads to the highest utility.   For that purpose I developed a prediction mechanism applied on large-scale graphs, for anticipating possible opponent knowledge in competitive game contexts, used for decision making. The mechanism is inspired from techniques used in the field of Data Science and Machine Learning, e.g., statistical inference, link analysis, Bayesian networks and relies on the use of Monte Carlo simulations.

headline: ML Engineer @ JPMorgan Chase | ML / NLP Grad @ CMU
summary: Hey! I'm an Applied AI/ML Engineer at JPMorgan Chase & Co., working on some interesting problems in the space of NLP and recommender systems.  Prior to CMU, I completed my Master's in Intelligent Information Systems in the School of Computer Science at Carnegie Mellon University, where I was advised by Dr. Alan W. Black.  My interests lie in the areas of Machine Learning, Deep Learning, and Natural Language Processing. Over the past summer, I interned at Adobe Sensei, where I developed an efficient encoder and latent space optimization based technique to invert GANs for semantic image editing.   My research at CMU has been focused on various topics in NLP, such as Detecting Entailment in low-resource code-mixed settings, Question-Answering on Scientific documents, and Causality Detection in Financial Documents, all of which are published at EMNLP and COLING workshops this year. Prior to CMU, I conducted research on image processing, and published my work on Detecting Diabetic Retinopathy from Retinal Images as an ACM paper to the proceedings of ICBBB 2019. I received the best paper presentation award for this conference held at the National University of Singapore.
